1 person’s opportunity for social and financial independence. Those benefits and
2 services include, but are not limited to:
3 (1) education services for a person under guardianship who is of school
4 age;
5 (2) residential services for a person under guardianship who lacks
6 adequate housing;
7 (3) nutrition services;
8 (4) medical and dental services, including home health care;
9 (5) therapeutic and habilitative services, adult education, vocational
10 rehabilitation, or other appropriate services.
11 (c) The guardian shall always serve the interests of the person under
12 guardianship and shall bring any potential conflicts of interest to the attention
13 of the court.
14 (d)(1) When the court appoints a guardian for an adult with disabilities, the
15 court shall ensure that the guardian understands the powers and duties of
16 guardianship and complies with the following requirements of a mandatory
17 training program jointly established by the Probate Division of the Superior
18 Court and the Department of Disabilities, Aging, and Independent Living:
19 (A) The training shall include a review of a guardianship handbook
20 approved by the Probate Division of the Superior Court and the Department of
21 Disabilities, Aging and Independent Living.
